01:02.999 --> 01:04.299
(wind whistling)

01:08.004 --> 01:11.506
S-So lonely.

01:13.676 --> 01:16.845
(raspy): No sex
without a ring.

01:18.881 --> 01:20.582
Damn it!

01:20.616 --> 01:23.051
(gentle orchestral music
continues, giants laughing)

01:24.453 --> 01:26.054
(belches)

01:36.399 --> 01:38.767
(creaking)

01:38.801 --> 01:41.236
♪

01:44.040 --> 01:45.173
Mm.

01:45.207 --> 01:46.474
What the...?! Hey, whoa!

01:47.877 --> 01:49.611
(ghostly moaning)

01:49.645 --> 01:51.646
(crackling)

01:55.618 --> 01:57.385
What about us, man?

01:57.420 --> 01:59.020
Get your own couch.

01:59.055 --> 02:01.156
♪

02:05.694 --> 02:07.695
(soft organ music playing)

02:09.365 --> 02:12.333
(organ music continues)

02:13.869 --> 02:17.806
Poor Chip. Such a big part
of everyone's life.

02:17.840 --> 02:20.275
People called him
the "sixth Simpson."

02:20.309 --> 02:21.843
I'm not sure why.

02:21.877 --> 02:26.281
Chip did such a wonderful job
with my biography.

02:26.315 --> 02:28.316
(people murmuring)

02:34.223 --> 02:38.660
Chip was the life of Sector 6-F
at the nuclear plant,

02:38.694 --> 02:43.264
but Chip once confessed to me
he did have a few regrets.

02:43.299 --> 02:44.332
(all gasp)

02:44.366 --> 02:46.334
Chip regretted never ascending

02:46.368 --> 02:48.837
Mount Springfield
from the <i>south</i> face.

02:48.871 --> 02:52.207
He regretted that the high
school long jump record he set

02:52.241 --> 02:53.842
was wind-aided.

02:53.876 --> 02:57.112
He often spoke of that asterisk.

02:57.146 --> 03:01.149
He never broke par on hole 17
at Springfield Mini Golf.

03:01.183 --> 03:03.618
(organ music resumes)
Let us pray.

03:03.652 --> 03:05.353
Eh, everyone has regrets.

03:05.387 --> 03:06.621
Not me.

03:06.655 --> 03:08.890
You? Your marriage
is a dead fish

03:08.924 --> 03:11.226
floating in a tank
of stale beer.

03:11.260 --> 03:13.862
Your baby's addicted
to pacifiers.

03:16.398 --> 03:18.733
And your son is
out of control.

03:19.568 --> 03:21.069
Let us kneel.

03:26.876 --> 03:28.843
(pained groans)
Ow! My knees!

03:28.878 --> 03:31.579
40 years of healing, gone!

03:31.614 --> 03:33.348
(cackling)

03:33.382 --> 03:35.316
He's such a little dickens.

03:35.351 --> 03:37.819
Although Dickens
was pretty well behaved.

03:37.853 --> 03:40.355
He's been screwed up since
the moment Homer's DNA

03:40.389 --> 03:42.157
staggered into your womb.

03:42.191 --> 03:43.992
I have no regrets about that.

03:44.026 --> 03:46.094
It was a perfect pregnancy.

03:46.128 --> 03:49.564
Didn't smoke, didn't drink,
lost <i>three pounds.</i>

03:49.598 --> 03:50.832
And every night before bed,

03:50.866 --> 03:52.700
Homer would give me
a little kiss...

03:52.735 --> 03:54.169
music! (gasps)

03:54.203 --> 03:56.671
Could Bart have been
prenatally screwed up

03:56.705 --> 03:59.040
by the KISS music?

03:59.074 --> 04:01.743
♪ Get up! Everybody's
gonna move their feet ♪

04:01.777 --> 04:04.846
♪ Get down! Everybody's
gonna leave their seats ♪

04:04.880 --> 04:08.383
♪ You got to lose your mind
in Detroit Rock City. ♪

04:09.552 --> 04:10.852
Huh?

04:10.886 --> 04:14.422
Man, this is the weirdest
pregnancy craving ever.

04:14.456 --> 04:16.757
Well, for some reason
it relaxes me.

04:16.791 --> 04:18.860
Now, do that thing
Gene Simmons does.

04:18.894 --> 04:21.228
Overstay my welcome
for 40 years?

04:22.965 --> 04:25.400
(whistling a tune)

04:25.434 --> 04:28.403
KENT BROCKMAN: <i>Regrets, eh?</i>
<i>This local newsman's had a few.</i>

04:28.437 --> 04:30.371
<i>Covering a town</i>
<i>of backwater rubes</i>

04:30.406 --> 04:32.740
<i>who, for some reason,</i>
<i>hate my guts.</i>

04:32.775 --> 04:35.210
This is Kent Brockman...
(sighs)

04:35.244 --> 04:37.768
live at the Springfield
Peach Parade.

04:37.769 --> 04:40.950
Sir, could you give us eight
seconds of your homespun wisdom?

04:41.317 --> 04:42.784
It's a little-known fact

04:42.818 --> 04:45.520
that you can get
head lice from peaches.

04:45.554 --> 04:47.555
Uh, this is my
daughter Peaches.

04:47.590 --> 04:50.358
(sighs) We'll have more regrets
at 11:00 tonight

04:50.392 --> 04:52.427
following an all-new
bottle of scotch.

04:52.461 --> 04:54.295
HOMER (scoffs):
You <i>have regrets,</i>

04:54.330 --> 04:57.031
<i>Mr. "I Get to See the</i>
<i>Weathergirl From the Side"!</i>

04:57.066 --> 05:00.068
<i>I made the worst financial</i>
<i>decision of all time.</i>

05:00.102 --> 05:01.803
<i>Oh, I can't think about it.</i>

05:01.837 --> 05:03.404
<i>I won't think about it.</i>

05:03.439 --> 05:05.240
<i>I don't want to think about it!</i>

05:05.274 --> 05:08.676
<i>Oh, I'm thinking about it!</i>

05:10.179 --> 05:11.279
Mm...

05:12.948 --> 05:14.082
Hmm.

05:14.116 --> 05:15.416
Huh?

05:15.451 --> 05:18.253
(shudders): Oh...
that's the coolest bowling ball

05:18.287 --> 05:20.121
I've ever seen.

05:21.690 --> 05:23.224
Hello, Bear Stearns?

05:23.259 --> 05:25.426
I'd like to sell
all my Apple stock

05:25.461 --> 05:27.595
so I can buy
a fancy bowling ball.

05:27.630 --> 05:30.298
You heard me.
Technology is a fad.

05:30.332 --> 05:32.834
Heavy, black balls
are the future.

05:34.036 --> 05:36.471
Now let us text
on our ubiquitous

05:36.505 --> 05:38.873
Apple tablets and phones.

05:38.907 --> 05:40.208
(keys clicking)

05:41.377 --> 05:44.712
Oh, you cost me a
piece of all that!

05:45.714 --> 05:47.415
Oh, don't cry.

05:47.449 --> 05:49.317
If it makes you
feel worse,

05:49.351 --> 05:51.486
<i>I'm</i> the man who bought
the stock you sold.

05:51.520 --> 05:54.989
I'll bet a rich man like you
has no regrets at all.

05:55.024 --> 05:56.658
Just one.

05:56.692 --> 05:58.493
The girl that got away.

05:58.527 --> 06:00.795
She broke my first heart.

06:00.829 --> 06:04.966
So, is there truly anyone
among us without regrets?

06:05.000 --> 06:06.367
I have no regrets.

06:06.402 --> 06:07.635
Really, Mother?

06:07.670 --> 06:10.338
Oh, I didn't
see you there.

06:15.079 --> 06:18.270
(Irish accent): I'm Father O'Greedy.
Dimes for the needy.

06:18.271 --> 06:19.773
(Milhouse chuckles)

06:19.873 --> 06:22.841
Milhouse, are you the bottom
half of that mischief?

06:22.876 --> 06:26.378
MILHOUSE:
Uh... uh... uh...

06:26.413 --> 06:28.113
Oh, my.

06:28.148 --> 06:31.850
My pants, like the Lord,
work in mysterious ways.

06:31.885 --> 06:33.452
Return those vestments.

06:33.486 --> 06:35.020
Speaking of return
on investments,

06:35.055 --> 06:37.323
my Apple stock
is up 3,500%.

06:37.357 --> 06:39.725
Aw, you misheard that
on purpose!

06:41.394 --> 06:43.062
(grunting)

06:43.096 --> 06:46.465
Tithe denied!
Tithe denied!

06:46.499 --> 06:50.970
Mm. Must find way...
to blame myself.

06:52.372 --> 06:55.574
Um, it says I should
give you lumbar support.

06:55.608 --> 06:57.776
Better go to
the lumber yard.

06:57.811 --> 07:00.312
"Lum- <i>bar."</i>
It means "lower back."

07:00.347 --> 07:02.748
How many times
will you make that mistake?

07:02.782 --> 07:04.850
(groans) Just put on
the KISS record.

07:04.884 --> 07:07.186
Which one?
Anything from <i>Love Gun.</i>

07:07.220 --> 07:08.487
♪

07:08.521 --> 07:11.757
Hey, book,
are you expecting <i>this?</i>

07:11.791 --> 07:13.125
And while I'm at it...

07:13.159 --> 07:16.595
Burn, dumb, helpful books.

07:16.629 --> 07:18.630
That is a <i>good</i> fire.

07:18.665 --> 07:20.666
(grunting)

07:20.700 --> 07:22.534
(pants)

07:22.569 --> 07:24.770
You're going down, Bart!

07:24.804 --> 07:27.039
(grunts, groans)

07:27.073 --> 07:29.274
Ah, reckless youth.
He'll be okay.

07:29.309 --> 07:30.876
I was referring to <i>him.</i>

07:32.212 --> 07:35.280
I had a spring in my
step like that once.

07:35.315 --> 07:37.716
Back when I met Lilah.

07:37.751 --> 07:41.754
<i>Lilah ran a little crepe stand</i>
<i>in the seventh arrondissement.</i>

07:43.356 --> 07:45.057
Oh, Monty,

07:45.091 --> 07:49.528
looking at you, I could lie
in this unheated garret forever.

07:49.562 --> 07:51.497
There's heat.
I just don't turn it on.

07:51.531 --> 07:54.800
Seeing you there, in the sweet
light of Paris between the wars,

07:54.834 --> 07:56.568
there's a question I must pose.

07:56.603 --> 07:57.970
I have something for you.

07:58.004 --> 07:59.972
Oh! Not that.

08:00.006 --> 08:01.974
(chuckles)

08:02.008 --> 08:03.175
(grunts)

08:03.209 --> 08:04.476
(bubbling)

08:04.511 --> 08:05.711
(chuckles)

08:07.947 --> 08:11.250
Wrong box. Lilah,
will you take that big step

08:11.284 --> 08:13.218
from cousin to wife?
(gasps)

08:13.253 --> 08:16.155
Oh, Monty, you must
promise me one thing.

08:16.189 --> 08:18.524
Anything she wanted
I was willing to do.

08:18.558 --> 08:20.559
Anything, except...

08:20.593 --> 08:23.062
All I ask is that you set aside

08:23.096 --> 08:25.697
five minutes a day
to think of others.

08:25.732 --> 08:28.767
When you say "others,"
could they be bars of gold?

08:28.802 --> 08:31.336
(crying):
I shall find another husband

08:31.371 --> 08:33.605
as good as you are evil.

08:33.640 --> 08:34.640
No one's that good.

08:34.674 --> 08:36.842
(sobbing)

08:36.876 --> 08:40.379
All I have left is my drawing.

08:40.413 --> 08:43.381
Hm. It looked a lot better
in my memory.

08:43.416 --> 08:45.084
Uh, but you know what, Smithers?

08:45.118 --> 08:47.553
I will find Lilah
and win her back.

08:47.587 --> 08:49.555
I'll just check
with the old gang.

08:49.589 --> 08:50.889
Hemingway!

08:51.658 --> 08:52.591
Picasso.

08:53.393 --> 08:55.160
Matador Juan Belmonte.

08:56.229 --> 08:58.530
And Stalin.

08:58.565 --> 09:00.632
That man could really
put pressure on you.

09:00.667 --> 09:01.900
Hello, Kent.

09:01.935 --> 09:04.369
Well, well, well.
Rachel Maddow.

09:04.404 --> 09:06.405
Everyone came back
for Chip's funeral.

09:06.439 --> 09:08.974
I was flying from DC to New York
and, of course,

09:09.008 --> 09:10.342
I had the layover
in Springfield.

09:10.376 --> 09:12.077
How's the gang at Channel 6?

09:12.112 --> 09:14.346
Look, let's get this out of the way--
just because we both

09:14.380 --> 09:16.548
worked at Channel 6 and
you made it big and I didn't

09:16.583 --> 09:19.384
doesn't mean I'm bitter.
Um, Is that your car?

09:19.419 --> 09:21.153
Maybe.

09:21.187 --> 09:22.588
Kent, I'm
gonna tell you

09:22.622 --> 09:25.157
the most important
mistake you ever made...

09:25.191 --> 09:26.692
after this break.

09:26.726 --> 09:28.994
So, Kent, that
mistake you made,

09:29.028 --> 09:30.996
that fundamental,
life-changing error,

09:31.030 --> 09:32.698
that cosmic fail, that...

09:32.732 --> 09:35.167
Just tell me already!
After this break.

09:35.201 --> 09:36.668
You could have
come with me,

09:36.703 --> 09:38.403
but you were suckling
the dual teats

09:38.438 --> 09:41.607
of infotainment
and celebrifawning.

09:41.641 --> 09:43.542
(upbeat theme plays)

09:43.576 --> 09:45.577
So, tell us about
your new movie.

09:45.612 --> 09:47.112
It's fantastic.

09:47.147 --> 09:50.249
The studio let us play
in their sandbox.

09:50.283 --> 09:52.751
Great. We have a clip.
No! No, don't show it.

09:52.785 --> 09:55.387
There aren't five good seconds
in the whole film.

09:55.421 --> 09:56.788
(car door closes,
tires screeching)

09:58.158 --> 10:00.859
I'm not a newsman anymore,
I'm a geologist.

10:00.894 --> 10:02.895
I keep discovering
a new rock bottom.

10:02.929 --> 10:05.797
Kent, I think I found my
ticket out of this town.

10:05.832 --> 10:07.966
Or at least to a
<i>better</i> Springfield.

10:08.001 --> 10:10.068
You two newshounds
working on a story?

10:10.103 --> 10:11.870
How about this?

10:11.905 --> 10:14.907
Mario's down the street
found a rat in their pasta.

10:14.941 --> 10:16.475
When did that happen?

10:16.509 --> 10:18.477
Whenever you want. Eh?

10:18.511 --> 10:19.912
Rachel, can I come?

10:19.946 --> 10:21.313
We can share blazers.

10:21.347 --> 10:22.881
Just follow me.

10:22.916 --> 10:25.417
At Mario's, the picture
of Sinatra on the wall

10:25.451 --> 10:27.452
is signed by Frank Junior.

10:27.487 --> 10:29.621
The frame hides the "Junior"!

10:29.656 --> 10:32.624
Someone's been dumping tires
in the forest.

10:34.427 --> 10:36.395
Willikers!
In my three years of soft news,

10:36.429 --> 10:37.996
I've never seen
anything like this.

10:38.031 --> 10:41.466
Those are tires from my
ill-fated Krusty Town Car.

10:41.501 --> 10:44.503
It would <i>explode</i> if people
gripped the wheel too tightly.

10:44.537 --> 10:46.071
(laughs):
What a scoop!

10:46.105 --> 10:47.673
You're not telling no one.

10:47.707 --> 10:50.742
As the 4:00 p.m. clown,
I have complete control

10:50.777 --> 10:53.045
of the Channel 6 news division.

10:54.681 --> 10:56.515
Local news is a joke.

10:56.549 --> 10:58.150
I'm going to cable.

10:58.184 --> 10:59.585
Cable news!

10:59.619 --> 11:02.287
Bah! People only want news
at 6:00 p.m.

11:02.322 --> 11:04.122
from white guys on weekdays

11:04.157 --> 11:05.991
and black guys on weekends.

11:06.025 --> 11:07.292
We'll see about that.

11:07.327 --> 11:09.127
Yes, we shall see.

11:09.162 --> 11:11.463
About that,
things will be seen.

11:11.497 --> 11:13.498
By us.

11:14.734 --> 11:15.867
Kent, you coming?

11:15.902 --> 11:17.336
He ain't comin'.

11:17.370 --> 11:19.504
This little piggy's
afraid to leave his cushy

11:19.539 --> 11:21.473
anchorman slop trough.

11:21.507 --> 11:23.942
Could you, uh, phrase that
a little more nicely?

11:23.977 --> 11:26.712
Sorry. He "isn't" coming.

11:26.746 --> 11:28.280
You'll regret this, Kent.

11:28.314 --> 11:30.682
When I have my own show
and you're stuck here

11:30.717 --> 11:33.218
tracking Santa's flight
from the North Pole.

11:33.253 --> 11:35.254
"Oh, look, he's
over Greenland!"

11:39.359 --> 11:42.427
Don't worry, piggy,
you made the right choice.

11:44.330 --> 11:47.933
Eh, it'll burn out
in an hour or so.

11:53.706 --> 11:54.106
Grunting as he lifts
Bryce in the air.

11:55.087 --> 11:57.556
Look, Burns, I've got the dope
on your sweetie.

11:57.656 --> 11:59.624
She's still alive,
and she just got over

11:59.658 --> 12:01.425
being mad at you last week.

12:01.660 --> 12:02.960
Lilah's alive?

12:02.994 --> 12:04.495
Yeah, well, uh,
she's alive,

12:04.529 --> 12:06.464
<i>but</i> she's a nun.

12:06.498 --> 12:08.799
Married to Jesus, eh?
Does he beat her?

12:08.834 --> 12:11.302
Jesus? No, he's a real
Eagle Scout, that one.

12:11.336 --> 12:14.238
But your penguin's not a Catholic,
she's a Buddhist nun--

12:14.272 --> 12:17.741
spent her life expressing her
sexuality with a Zen garden.

12:17.776 --> 12:19.643
Those raked rocks
could have been me.

12:19.678 --> 12:23.013
Now, since you're so good at
finding things, find the exit.

12:23.048 --> 12:26.016
There is the little
matter of my fee.

12:26.051 --> 12:28.252
You're becoming very tiresome.

12:28.286 --> 12:29.854
Who moved my desk?!

12:29.888 --> 12:32.857
♪

12:34.960 --> 12:37.394
Well, here I am.
Cable news alley.

12:42.067 --> 12:44.068
(dog howls)

12:46.204 --> 12:48.138
Fox News.
Is this <i>really</i> how I want

12:48.173 --> 12:49.840
to get back in the big leagues?

12:49.875 --> 12:51.542
Let's see how
print journalism is doing.

12:51.576 --> 12:53.477
Sir, do you sell
<i>The New York Times?</i>

12:53.512 --> 12:56.046
Sir, we <i>are</i>
<i>The New York Times.</i>

12:56.081 --> 12:57.848
And in I go.

12:57.883 --> 13:00.384
Why are you doing
this, Bart?

13:00.418 --> 13:02.520
50% attention-seeking,

13:02.554 --> 13:05.523
50% to drop things on people.

13:05.557 --> 13:08.559
He's gonna visit
my sky granny.

13:08.593 --> 13:11.962
To work at Fox News,
all you have to be able to do

13:11.997 --> 13:13.631
is operate this device.

13:13.665 --> 13:15.699
Now, when a Republican
is in trouble...

13:15.734 --> 13:18.402
At the time,
I didn't know it was illegal

13:18.436 --> 13:21.305
to sex up a cow
on the Capitol steps.

13:21.339 --> 13:22.740
...we simply do this.

13:27.245 --> 13:29.713
Now you try.

13:33.852 --> 13:36.320
Sorry, but I just discovered
I have some scruples.

13:36.354 --> 13:38.422
I'm going back to
my sweet little town

13:38.456 --> 13:40.424
where <i>I</i> can decide
what news is.

13:40.458 --> 13:42.092
Like a god.

13:43.461 --> 13:45.563
We've had some good times.

13:45.597 --> 13:47.998
♪ Memories

13:48.033 --> 13:53.470
♪ Rest between the pages
of my mind ♪

13:56.141 --> 13:59.543
♪ Memories

13:59.578 --> 14:05.583
♪ See me through the ages
just like wine... ♪

14:05.617 --> 14:09.019
And you sat on the gas pedal
when my foot fell asleep,

14:09.054 --> 14:11.221
so I'm getting you
shined up nice.

14:11.256 --> 14:13.524
What the...?

14:13.558 --> 14:15.259
Oh!

14:15.293 --> 14:17.261
That's a ball-proof
window, sir.

14:17.295 --> 14:20.197
Would you like me to ask Siri
for a nearby hospital?

14:20.231 --> 14:24.134
SIRI: I'm sorry, I don't see
any "hops petals" near you.

14:24.169 --> 14:25.736
Deleting all
contact information.

14:25.770 --> 14:27.611
No, no, I didn't ask you
to do that, Siri. I...

14:27.639 --> 14:29.707
Delete confirmed.

14:33.661 --> 14:35.963
BART (groans):
Oh. Okay, Bart, be cool.

14:35.997 --> 14:38.665
Calm down, you're not
gonna die up here.

14:38.700 --> 14:39.967
(indistinct chatter)

14:40.001 --> 14:41.301
(whooping, gunfire)

14:41.336 --> 14:43.303
(yells, whimpers)

14:48.176 --> 14:49.710
Aw...

14:51.713 --> 14:52.780
D'oh!

15:03.892 --> 15:06.693
Oh, Monty, I can't
believe you found me

15:06.728 --> 15:08.896
after all these years.

15:08.930 --> 15:11.165
I've saved myself for you.

15:11.199 --> 15:12.499
Well, then, uh...
(nervous chuckle)

15:12.534 --> 15:14.234
I should disrobe at once.

15:14.269 --> 15:16.937
Housekeeping? Send up a
Chinese dressing screen

15:16.971 --> 15:20.107
and one of Firestone's finest
vulcanized prophylactics.

15:20.141 --> 15:22.743
Be right back.
(laughs softly)

15:25.213 --> 15:27.181
Smithers?
Which do I take first,

15:27.215 --> 15:29.283
the rhino horn
or the tiger tongue?

15:29.317 --> 15:31.018
I have my doubts
about both, sir.

15:31.052 --> 15:33.220
Bah! I'll just do it
the old-fashioned way.

15:33.254 --> 15:34.521
With my pump.

15:34.556 --> 15:36.857
(engine sputtering)

15:36.891 --> 15:38.592
(sputtering continues)

15:38.626 --> 15:40.561
(chuckles):
Just powdering my nose, darling.

15:40.595 --> 15:42.830
(engine continues sputtering)

15:44.732 --> 15:47.267
Smithers, run down
to Sears, Roebuck

15:47.302 --> 15:49.770
and get a five-eighths-inch
Phillips head bolt.

15:49.804 --> 15:51.772
(tires screech)

15:51.806 --> 15:54.441
(sighs) Here I am,
slowly dying every day

15:54.475 --> 15:56.443
at 5:00, 6:00 and 11:00.

15:56.477 --> 15:58.045
BART:
Help! Help!

15:58.079 --> 16:01.615
Child in danger
with exciting visuals!

16:01.649 --> 16:02.883
This kid's corpse could be

16:02.917 --> 16:04.785
my magic carpet.
Get me a cameraman!

16:04.819 --> 16:08.288
The movie <i>Up</i> has come horribly
to life over Springfield.

16:08.323 --> 16:10.490
A local boy
clings to life in a story

16:10.525 --> 16:12.459
that proves
this reporter's relevance.

16:12.493 --> 16:13.894
BART:
<i>Ay, caramba!</i>

16:13.928 --> 16:15.729
(gasps)
It's Bart!

16:15.763 --> 16:17.164
Pray for a miracle, boy.

16:17.198 --> 16:19.399
God can hear you
better from up there.

16:19.434 --> 16:21.401
Dear Lord, please
help me land safely.

16:21.436 --> 16:24.071
Or transform this basket
into a flying killer robot

16:24.105 --> 16:26.273
that I control
with my mind. Amen.

16:26.307 --> 16:27.441
That's not a prayer.

16:27.475 --> 16:29.142
My God says it is.

16:33.481 --> 16:36.683
Oh, I see you're ice-cold
with anticipation.

16:38.119 --> 16:39.920
Dead?

16:39.954 --> 16:41.455
Oh, Lilah.

16:41.489 --> 16:44.291
Even at the end,
I waited too long.

16:44.325 --> 16:46.660
What if I give her
the breath of life?

16:46.694 --> 16:48.128
(soft exhale)

16:48.162 --> 16:49.529
Oh, boy.

16:49.564 --> 16:51.598
I guess one regret
just leads to another.

16:51.633 --> 16:53.834
You know, sir, maybe it
would bring you peace

16:53.868 --> 16:56.403
to honor the one thing
Lilah ever asked of you.

16:59.507 --> 17:01.108
Here you are, my good man.

17:01.142 --> 17:03.443
A little broth will cure
your mental illness. (chuckles)

17:03.478 --> 17:04.810
Sir, that's
five minutes.

17:04.846 --> 17:06.880
You can stop thinking
of other people now.

17:06.915 --> 17:09.849
You know what, I think
I'll give it another five.

17:11.653 --> 17:14.288
I'm proud of you, Monty.

17:14.321 --> 17:15.622
(kissing)

17:15.656 --> 17:17.357
I ain't
eatin' that.

17:20.595 --> 17:23.030
Chief, what are you
doing to save our son?

17:23.064 --> 17:25.031
Well, I've placed marksmen
on the roof

17:25.066 --> 17:27.000
to shoot the balloons
one by one,

17:27.035 --> 17:28.869
but frankly
they're not very good.

17:28.903 --> 17:30.137
(gunshot)
(grunts)

17:30.171 --> 17:32.372
(whining): Chief,
it happened again.

17:32.407 --> 17:34.808
Aw, come on, guys,
spread out. Arm's length.

17:34.842 --> 17:36.243
It's all my fault.

17:36.277 --> 17:37.878
I should never have listened

17:37.912 --> 17:40.547
to those KISS albums
when I was pregnant.

17:40.581 --> 17:42.983
Marge, with all due respect,
that's ridiculous.

17:43.017 --> 17:45.419
My Sarah listened to Mozart
and Churchill speeches

17:45.453 --> 17:47.087
when she was pregnant
with Ralphie,

17:47.121 --> 17:49.389
and he can't even
open a refrigerator.

17:49.424 --> 17:51.091
Pushing, always...
always pushing.

17:51.125 --> 17:52.259
Really?

17:52.293 --> 17:54.027
Oh, yeah.
That kid's a mess.

17:54.062 --> 17:56.396
Hey! Only <i>I</i> get
to criticize him, Lou.

17:56.431 --> 17:58.865
Kid's scared to flush.
Think's it's his brother.

17:58.900 --> 18:02.102
Can we focus on my
son up in the sky?

18:02.136 --> 18:03.770
Oh, I've got
a long-shot idea.

18:03.805 --> 18:07.774
By which I mean firing a shot
over a long distance.

18:07.809 --> 18:09.543
(chuckling)

18:09.577 --> 18:11.178
Yeah, you see, if we could fire

18:11.212 --> 18:15.248
an exactly 12-and-a-half-pound
weight into the basket,

18:15.283 --> 18:18.552
it would lower the boy
very gently to the ground.

18:18.586 --> 18:22.022
Unfortunately, all our
cannonballs were melted down

18:22.056 --> 18:24.858
to make a statue
of Joe Paterno,

18:24.892 --> 18:27.494
which we changed
to look like Eugene Levy.

18:29.263 --> 18:32.632
I think I just might have
what you're looking for.

18:32.667 --> 18:36.436
♪

18:36.471 --> 18:40.207
Today I'm <i>glad</i> that
I sold that stock.

18:40.241 --> 18:42.943
Uh, Apple closed up
another 20 points today.

18:42.977 --> 18:44.878
(whining):
Why does everyone know?

18:44.912 --> 18:47.414
Because their terrific products
keep track of it for you.

18:47.448 --> 18:49.483
And anything else
you could ever think of.

18:56.257 --> 18:58.558
That kid's not
dying on <i>my</i> watch.

18:58.593 --> 19:00.761
Which ends... right
now, fortunately.

19:00.795 --> 19:02.429
(hums a tune)

19:04.932 --> 19:06.833
(whimpers)

19:06.868 --> 19:10.437
CROWD (chanting): Bart! Bart!
Bart! Bart! Bart! Bart!

19:10.471 --> 19:12.372
(laughing):
Hey.

19:12.407 --> 19:13.974
CROWD: Bart! Bart!
Hmm. (yells)

19:14.008 --> 19:16.243
Homer's rising faster
than Apple stock.

19:16.277 --> 19:17.644
(laughter)

19:17.678 --> 19:19.446
(Homer yells, grunts)

19:20.615 --> 19:22.582
My boy's okay!

19:22.617 --> 19:24.251
CROWD (chanting):
Bart! Bart! Bart!

19:24.285 --> 19:26.153
I won the
science fair!

19:26.187 --> 19:28.088
I get to go to Chicago!

19:28.122 --> 19:29.689
CROWD:
Bart! Bart! Bart!

19:29.724 --> 19:32.826
Ugh. Bart, Bart, Bart.

19:32.860 --> 19:34.861
You know what I think
about regrets?

19:34.896 --> 19:37.431
As long as your family
is together,

19:37.465 --> 19:40.434
every choice you've ever made
is the right one.

19:40.468 --> 19:42.202
And together we are.

19:42.236 --> 19:43.937
(gunshot)

19:43.971 --> 19:46.706
Would you guys knock it off?
He's down safe already.

19:46.741 --> 19:47.931
(gunshot)

19:47.956 --> 19:50.077
MAN: Sorry, Chief,
that was me putting it down.

19:50.078 --> 19:52.379
And there you have it--
a family reunited.

19:52.413 --> 19:55.382
And a grateful nation gives
thanks for some solid reporting.

19:55.416 --> 19:56.950
Back to you, Rachel Maddow.

19:56.984 --> 19:58.985
Great job, Kent.
I think we might have

19:59.020 --> 20:00.687
an opening for you at MSNBC

20:00.721 --> 20:02.656
between our weekend
prison documentary block

20:02.690 --> 20:04.624
and the two hours it takes

20:04.659 --> 20:06.693
to make up Joe Scarborough
on Monday morning.

20:06.727 --> 20:08.662
(chuckles): No, thanks, Rachel Maddow.
I'm happy right here.

20:08.696 --> 20:11.064
No regrets.

